04507nam a22005895i 9781501736421DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018056017  a97815017364217 a10.7591/97815017364212doi  a(DE-B1597)527508  a(OCoLC)1076370167  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL98.5 4aBL98.5b.G36 2019 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a201/.7209732231 aGamble, Richard M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Fiery Gospel :bThe Battle Hymn of the Republic and the Road to Righteous War /cRichard M. Gamble. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b22 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and American Public Life00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThe Battle Hymn of the Republic -- tPrologue -- t1. The Besieged City -- t2. A Rich Crimson -- t3. “The Glorious Freedom of His Gospel” -- t4. Righteous War and Holy Peace -- t5. The Anglo-American “Battle Hymn” -- t6. The Valor of Righteousness -- t7. The Sacred Inheritance of Mankind -- t8. Exotic Medley -- t9. A Severed Nation -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince its composition in Washington's Willard Hotel in 1861, Julia Ward Howe's "Battle Hymn of the Republic" has been used to make America and its wars sacred. Few Americans reflect on its violent and redemptive imagery, drawn freely from prophetic passages of the Old and New Testaments, and fewer still think about the implications of that apocalyptic language for how Americans interpret who they are and what they owe the world. In A Fiery Gospel, Richard M. Gamble describes how this camp-meeting tune, paired with Howe's evocative lyrics, became one of the most effective instruments of religious nationalism. He takes the reader back to the song's origins during the Civil War, and reveals how those political and military circumstances launched the song's incredible career in American public life. Gamble deftly considers the idea behind the song—humming the tune, reading the music for us—all while reveling in the multiplicity of meanings of and uses to which Howe's lyrics have been put. "The Battle Hymn of the Republic" has been versatile enough to match the needs of Civil Rights activists and conservative nationalists, war hawks and peaceniks, as well as Europeans and Americans. This varied career shows readers much about the shifting shape of American righteousness. Yet it is, argues Gamble, the creator of the song herself—her Abolitionist household, Unitarian theology, and Romantic and nationalist sensibilities—that is the true conductor of this most American of war songs. A Fiery Gospel depicts most vividly the surprising genealogy of "The Battle Hymn of the Republic," and its sure and certain position as a cultural piece in the uncertain amalgam that was and is American civil religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCivil religionzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aNationalismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aNationalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aCivil War. 4aMusical Arts & Ethnomusicology. 4aU.S. History. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198040uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173642140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501736421423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501736421.jpg  a978-3-11-065198-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles